reviewText: The course material is interesting but you cannot pass it without excel and XLMiner and other propietary software so I would not bother even starting. There are probably much better courses out there that use open source software.

Solver gave me a temporary license which quickly expired before I finished all the classes. I have contacted them multiple times. This course is honestly not worth the hassle of trying to get access to their software. The desktop version doesn't work on my computer and the 365 temporary trial quickly expired. This was one of the worst experiences I've had on coursera.
No Analytics just biz talk

I took the Advanced Business Analytics Specialization  as a full time student. I finished the first four courses in more or less 3 weeks. In the last course needed to take the Specialization Certificate, the Advanced Business Analytics Capstone, the assignments of the course during the 2nd-3rd-4rth week were locked until 20 December - 5 January. That means that I had to wait more than one month, and pay 2 more subscriptions to Coursera!!! In the forum of the class there are more than 20 moderators, none of them has even one reply in anything. I made a thread, nonone replied to me. I contacted the customer service, they told me that they are sorry and they cannot change it. This is not a policy of an educational institute, this is an attitude that wants to take only your money. If you want your certificate, come back after two months AND KEEP PAYING!! I canceled my subscription, I do not want the certificate, I want to cooperate with organization that respect my effort, my time, my money, to respect me. The course was fine.
don't take this course
I can't unenroll from this course, this is the stupidest flaw on your part!

The third part of the course (SQL) is just disappointing. You watch several videos where the instructor reads out SQL commands. There is no sample database you can work with right away the practice. In other courseras e.g.
Week 1:Databases and SQL for Data Science with Python by IBM.
 you got Short SQL videos and right away exercises online to practice the seen.At the end of week 3 then you have to pass an exam where you have to use the online database and write SQL commands. This is like somone reading a book about "Dancing" to you and at the end you have to participacte in a dance tournamante without practicing before. (As said before other courses to this much better)
On top of this the fonts in the video are hard to read as the background. 
Overall I would not recommend this course as it proune to frustrate the novice SQL learner.

Compared to Percipio counterpart, I don't find this Coursera part as applicable in my work as the Percipio one. There were too many divisions, splits, hierarchies, terms, models and roles which at the end of the day no one of us will remember and neither use. On the other hand, sometimes I felt like some points were teached too generally without required depth leading to still not understand what they are about and how can I use them or how should I treat them.

This format needs to be reassessed, as it is frustrating to those who have real world experience and are trying to further there knowledge base.

I enjoyed this course, and I learned a number of new skills and ideas that will be a direct benefit to me in my career.  My only suggestion for improving the course would be to revamp the quizzes.  For the most part, they were straight-forward, but in too many cases there were questions where material that was presented as subjective in lectures was made to be very objective on the quiz.  It was needlessly "hard" for the wrong reasons.  Quiz me on the material, but don't try to trip me up, that's not why I'm here.  I'm a professional, and I don't have time to re-take quizzes unnecessarily.

This
course provides
a good overview of what one might need to get started in
Data Analytics. It does not delve very deeply into any one topic.
This
could be consider both a good and a bad thing. Its superficiality
keeps students from getting lost in details, but it also keeps
students from some much needed deeper practical training which
generally aids in the development of true understanding of what the
theory is all about. Nevertheless, it is a good course, and students
may compensate for the lack of practice if they are willing to pause
the videos and recreate the material to run his examples on their
own.

I am taking this to round out my knowledge of how business analytics works in the business world. My only gripe is that we are expected to review three peer assignments to pass, and there are sometimes none to review!A word of advice here.
